<h1 class="chapter" id="part-a">PART A — FOUNDATIONS</h1>

<!-- CHAPTER 1 -->
<h1 class="chapter" id="ch1">Chapter 1: What is Vastu Shastra?</h1>
<p>Vastu Shastra is the ancient Indian science of architecture and spatial arrangement. The word <strong>Vastu</strong> derives from the Sanskrit root <em>Vas</em> — meaning "to dwell" or "to inhabit." Shastra means "science" or "scripture." Together, Vastu Shastra means the <strong>science of dwelling</strong>.</p>
<p>It is not a religion. It is not superstition. It is a systematic study of how the physical structure of a building — its orientation, proportions, room placement, and spatial relationships — affects the health, prosperity, and harmony of its occupants.</p>
<div class="highlight">
  <strong>Core Principle:</strong> Every structure exists within the forces of Nature — sunlight, wind, water, gravity, and electromagnetic fields. Vastu Shastra aligns the building with these natural forces so that the occupants benefit from them rather than resist them.
</div>
<h2 class="section">Ancient Sources</h2>
<p>Vastu Shastra is recorded in several ancient Indian texts called <strong>Vastu Agamas</strong>. The primary texts are:</p>
<table>
  <tr><th>Text</th><th>Tradition</th><th>Key Content</th></tr>
  <tr><td><strong>Viswakarma Prakashika</strong></td><td>Viswakarma tradition</td><td>Padavinyasa, 32 Devathas, Ayadi calculation</td></tr>
  <tr><td>Manasara</td><td>South Indian</td><td>Town planning, temple design, house Vastu</td></tr>
  <tr><td>Mayamata</td><td>Maya tradition</td><td>Residential Vastu, proportional systems</td></tr>
  <tr><td>Samarangana Sutradhara</td><td>North Indian</td><td>Palace design, fort planning</td></tr>
</table>
<p><strong>Samartha Vastu is based exclusively on the Viswakarma Prakashika</strong> — the most scientifically precise of all Vastu texts, employing proportional geometric calculation (Padavinyasa) rather than angular division.</p>

<!-- CHAPTER 2 -->
<h1 class="chapter" id="ch2">Chapter 2: Vastu Purusha — The Origin Story</h1>
<h2 class="section">The Mythology</h2>
<p>According to Vedic tradition, during a great cosmic war between the Devas (divine forces) and Asuras (demonic forces), Lord Shiva fought the demon Andhakasura. From the sweat of Shiva's forehead, a gigantic being was born — vast, powerful, and overwhelmingly hungry.</p>
<p>This being — the <strong>Vastu Purusha</strong> — demanded permission from Lord Shiva to devour the three worlds (Triloka). Frightened, the Devas appealed to Lord Brahma for protection.</p>
<p>Lord Brahma, assisted by the <strong>Ashta Dikapalas</strong> (the eight guardians of the eight directions), commanded 45 divine beings to pin the Vastu Purusha face-down upon the earth. He was pinned with:</p>
<ul style="color:#cbd5e1;padding-left:20px;margin-bottom:14px;">
  <li>Head toward the <strong>North-East</strong> (Ishanya — most sacred direction)</li>
  <li>Feet toward the <strong>South-West</strong> (Nairutya — most stable direction)</li>
  <li>Lord Brahma himself sitting at the <strong>centre</strong> (Brahma Sthana)</li>
</ul>
<div class="highlight green">
  <strong>Symbolic meaning:</strong> Vastu Purusha represents the living energy within every plot of land. When a building is constructed correctly according to Vastu principles, the Vastu Purusha is at peace — and the occupants prosper. When the building violates Vastu, the Vastu Purusha is disturbed — and the occupants suffer.
</div>

