<!-- CHAPTER 3 -->
<h1 class="chapter" id="ch3">Chapter 3: What is Padavinyasa?</h1>
<p><strong>Padavinyasa</strong> (पादविन्यास) comes from two Sanskrit words: <em>Pada</em> (step or unit of measurement) and <em>Vinyasa</em> (arrangement or placement). It is the method of arranging the 32 Devathas (divine guardians) proportionally around the perimeter of any plot or building.</p>
<div class="highlight blue">
  <strong>Key Principle:</strong> In Padavinyasa, the Devathas are placed PROPORTIONALLY along the actual wall lengths — not at fixed angular positions from the centre. A 30-foot wall and a 60-foot wall will have different Devatha spans even though they face the same direction.
</div>
<h2 class="section">How Padavinyasa Works</h2>
<p>Each side of the plot is divided into 9 units called <strong>Padas</strong>:</p>
<table>
  <tr><th>Position</th><th>Devatha Count</th><th>Notes</th></tr>
  <tr><td>Each corner</td><td>½ Devatha (shared)</td><td>Corner Devathas are split between two sides</td></tr>
  <tr><td>Each side (between corners)</td><td>7 full Devathas</td><td>Spans proportional to wall length</td></tr>
  <tr><td>Total perimeter</td><td>4×½×2 + 4×7 = 32</td><td>32 unique Devatha positions</td></tr>
</table>
<p>The chain runs: <strong>NE → SE (East face) → SE → SW (South face) → SW → NW (West face) → NW → NE (North face)</strong></p>

<!-- CHAPTER 4 — Sakkhi Chakra Proof -->
<h1 class="chapter" id="ch4">Chapter 4: Why Sakkhi Chakra is Scientifically Wrong</h1>
<div class="special-note">
  <h3>⚠️ Special Note — Scientific Proof</h3>
  <p>This chapter presents the original research by the creators of Samartha Vastu, validated by independent scientific analysis. The Sakkhi Chakra method, used by most North Indian Vastu software, contains fundamental geometric and geographic errors.</p>
</div>
<h2 class="section">What is the Sakkhi Chakra?</h2>
<p>The Sakkhi Chakra is a circular tool that places Devatha positions at fixed angular intervals (22.5° each for 16 zones) radiating from the centre of a plot, using a magnetic compass to determine North.</p>
<h2 class="section">Proof 1: The Parallel North Proof</h2>
<p>Geographic directions (North, South, East, West) are defined by lines of <strong>latitude and longitude</strong> — which run as parallel lines across the entire surface of the Earth.</p>
<div class="proof-box">Stand at the SW corner of your plot.
Your compass shows 0° North.

Walk 50 feet to the SE corner.
Your compass STILL shows 0° North.

Walk 100 feet to the NE corner.
Your compass STILL shows 0° North.

The North direction runs through EVERY POINT of
your plot like parallel railway tracks.

It does NOT radiate from the centre.
It does NOT change based on plot shape.
It does NOT rotate when the plot is elongated.</div>

<!-- SVG Diagram 2: Parallel North Proof -->
<svg class="diagram" viewBox="0 0 500 280" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" style="max-width:480px;background:#0f1f35;border-radius:12px;padding:16px;">
