<h2 class="section">Proof 2: The Rectangle = Two Squares</h2>
<div class="proof-box">A 30×60 rectangle is simply two 30×30 squares joined:

[SQUARE 1] + [SQUARE 2] = [RECTANGLE]
  30×30        30×30        30×60

East wall of Square 1 = 30ft, faces East ✅
East wall of Square 2 = 30ft, faces East ✅

Therefore:
East wall of Rectangle = 60ft, faces East ✅

The East did NOT turn for Square 1.
The East did NOT turn for Square 2.
Therefore the East CANNOT turn for the Rectangle.

Q.E.D. — Geometric proof. Undeniable.</div>

<h2 class="section">Proof 3: Magnetic Compass is Unreliable</h2>
<table>
  <tr><th>City</th><th>Magnetic Declination</th><th>Error on 40ft wall</th></tr>
  <tr class="bad-row"><td>Delhi</td><td>+1.31°</td><td>~11 inches error</td></tr>
  <tr><td>Mumbai</td><td>−0.84°</td><td>~7 inches error</td></tr>
  <tr><td>Hyderabad</td><td>−0.51°</td><td>~4 inches error</td></tr>
  <tr><td>Bangalore</td><td>−0.55°</td><td>~5 inches error</td></tr>
  <tr><td>Chennai</td><td>−0.33°</td><td>~3 inches error</td></tr>
</table>
<p>Additionally: Steel reinforcement bars, electrical wiring, water pipes, and mobile towers all deflect the compass needle. A compass reading taken inside or near a constructed building measures <strong>iron and electricity</strong> — not the Earth.</p>
<div class="warn">
  <strong>Historical proof:</strong> The Viswakarma Prakashika was written over 3,000 years ago. The magnetic compass arrived in India approximately 900–1000 AD — 2,000 years AFTER the Vastu texts. The original method for finding North was the <strong>Shanku (Gnomon)</strong> — a vertical stick whose shadow gives exact astronomical True North. This is identical to what modern GPS satellites provide.
</div>

<!-- CHAPTER 5 -->
<h1 class="chapter" id="ch5">Chapter 5: True North vs Magnetic North</h1>
<div class="comparison">
  <div class="wrong-col">
    <h4>❌ Magnetic North (Compass)</h4>
    <p>Points to the magnetic North Pole</p>
    <p>Drifts up to 25° per century</p>
    <p>Deflected by steel, wiring, metal</p>
    <p>Different in every city</p>
    <p>Changes measurement year to year</p>
    <p>Used by Sakkhi Chakra — no Vedic authority</p>
  </div>
  <div class="right-col">
    <h4>✅ True North (Astronomical)</h4>
    <p>Points to geographic North Pole</p>
    <p>Fixed — never changes</p>
    <p>Not affected by materials</p>
    <p>Same everywhere on Earth</p>
    <p>Same measurement every century</p>
    <p>Used by Viswakarma Prakashika — Vedic authority</p>
  </div>
</div>
<div class="highlight">
  <strong>In Samartha Vastu:</strong> Enter your site's True North degree from Google Maps satellite view or survey document. The software uses this exact value for all 32 Devatha calculations. If you only have a compass reading, use the Magnetic Declination correction in the Site Geometry section.
</div>

<!-- ═══════════ PART B — THE SYSTEM ═══════════ -->
<h1 class="chapter" id="part-b">PART B — THE PADAVINYASA SYSTEM</h1>

<!-- CHAPTER 6 -->
<h1 class="chapter" id="ch6">Chapter 6: The 9×9 Pada Grid</h1>
<p>The fundamental unit of Vastu planning in Viswakarma Prakashika is the <strong>9×9 Pada Grid</strong> — also called the <strong>Paramasayika Mandala</strong>. It divides the plot into 81 equal squares (padas).</p>
<table>
  <tr><th>Zone</th><th>Location</th><th>Deity</th><th>Significance</th></tr>
  <tr class="good-row"><td>Brahma Sthana</td><td>Centre 4 padas</td><td>Brahma</td><td>Most sacred — must remain open</td></tr>
  <tr><td>Outer ring</td><td>32 perimeter padas</td><td>32 Devathas</td><td>Govern entrances and activities</td></tr>
  <tr><td>Middle ring</td><td>28 intermediate padas</td><td>12 inner Devathas</td><td>Internal energy distribution</td></tr>
  <tr class="bad-row"><td>Marma Sthanas</td><td>8 specific intersections</td><td>—</td><td>Sacred joints — never pierce</td></tr>
</table>
<div class="highlight">
  <strong>Brahma Sthana Rule:</strong> The central 4 padas (Brahma Sthana) must always be kept open — no columns, no walls, no heavy storage. This is the breathing space of the house. In apartment buildings, this corresponds to the central courtyard or light well.
</div>

